and outspoken proponents on both sides of the debate, this volume provides the first comprehensive analysis of the issues involved in administering a system of essentially private social security accounts. The contributors together come to startlingly similar conclusions, generally agreeing that a centralized system of accounts could deliver the benefits of privatization in a feasible and cost-efficient way by accessing administrative mechanisms already in existence. This is perhaps the most far-reaching synthesis yet envisioned of functional and implementable social security reform.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBusiness. 0aPrivatization. 0aSocial sciences. 0aSocial security individual investment accounts. 0aSocial security. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAhern, F. Gregory, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiamond, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDickson, Joel M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerrier, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldberg, Fred T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraetz, Michael J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrauer, Frederick L. A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJames, Estelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMathews, Shaun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPoterba, James M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPozen, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchieber, Sylvester J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShoven, John B., eco